# API & Server Action rules

Keep handlers **thin** — validate input, call `src/lib/domain/`, map errors to HTTP/action responses.

## Auth

- Server Actions: `requireActionSession()` from `src/lib/api/require-session.ts` first.
- API routes: `requireApiSession()` (returns `{ error }` response on failure) — middleware does NOT protect `/api/*`.
- Cron routes: verify `CRON_SECRET` Bearer via `isAuthorizedCronRequest` (`src/lib/cron-auth.ts`), then gate on automation source with `gateCronOrRun` (`src/lib/cron-gate.ts`).
- Never import edge-incompatible DB auth in `middleware.ts` — use `@/lib/auth.config` only.

## Validation

- Zod schemas at the boundary; env access through `src/lib/env.ts` (`loadServerEnv()`).

## Responses

- Server Actions return `{ error?: string }` (plus optional payload fields); call `revalidatePath()` for affected dashboards after writes.
- API routes return `NextResponse.json`; cron handlers return `{ ok, skipped?, reason? }`.
- Never return stack traces to clients in production.

## Cron routes

`/api/cron/*`: sheet-sync, unbriefed-panels, kaz-panel-slack, rp-slack, factory-fill, export-sync, var-panel-slack, factory-deadline-slack — schedules in `vercel.json`. Collectors live in `src/lib/domain/`; routes only auth + gate + call.

## Do NOT

- Put business rules inline in route handlers
- Skip auth on routes exposed to the internet
- Bypass automation toggles when adding a new cron or Slack notification
